---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import LineageContextBanner from '../../components/LineageContextBanner.tsx';
import Claim from '../../components/Claim.astro';
import FactTier from '../../components/FactTier.astro';
import VarnaJatiLocator from '../../components/viz/VarnaJatiLocator.astro';
import RelatedNav from '../../components/site/RelatedNav.astro';

const communities = [
  {
    en: 'Kongu Vellala Gounder',
    ta: 'கொங்கு வேளாள கவுண்டர்',
    region: 'Kongu Nadu (western Tamil Nadu)',
    note: 'The user’s community. Vellala cultivator caste-cluster with 145-kootam structure. By far the largest and most-cited Gounder community.',
    highlight: true,
  },
  {
    en: 'Vettuva Gounder',
    ta: 'வேட்டுவ கவுண்டர்',
    region: 'Salem, Erode, Coimbatore',
    note: 'Traditionally a hunter-warrior community (வேட்டுவன் = hunter). Distinct lineage and history from Kongu Vellala despite sharing the title.',
  },
  {
    en: 'Urali Gounder',
    ta: 'உராளி கவுண்டர்',
    region: 'Erode, Coimbatore',
    note: 'Administrators / land-managers; distinct community though regionally adjacent.',
  },
  {
    en: 'Nattu Gounder',
    ta: 'நாட்டு கவுண்டர்',
    region: 'North Tamil Nadu',
    note: 'Smaller community using the title; separate lineage.',
  },
  {
    en: 'Kurumba Gounder',
    ta: 'குறும்ப கவுண்டர்',
    region: 'Nilgiris',
    note: 'Pastoralist community in the Nilgiris hills; entirely separate community from the plains-Vellala Gounders.',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Gounder — Decoded"
  description="Deep-dive on the Gounder title — its etymology, function as village headman, and how multiple unrelated Tamil communities use the same title."
>
  <main id="main-content" class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-6 py-12 sm:py-16">
    <LineageContextBanner client:load />
    <nav class="mb-8 text-sm text-stone-500">
      <a href="/" class="hover:text-stone-900 rounded focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-indigo-500 focus-visible:ring-offset-2 focus-visible:ring-offset-stone-50">Home</a>
      <span class="mx-2" aria-hidden="true">/</span>
      <a href="/lineage" class="hover:text-stone-900 rounded focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-indigo-500 focus-visible:ring-offset-2 focus-visible:ring-offset-stone-50">Lineage</a>
      <span class="mx-2" aria-hidden="true">/</span>
      <span class="text-stone-700">Gounder</span>
    </nav>

    <VarnaJatiLocator highlightSlug="kongu-vellala" class="mb-6" />

    <header class="mb-10">
      <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-amber-700">Title · பட்டம்</p>
      <h1 class="mt-2 text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight sm:text-5xl">
        <span class="block">Gounder</span>
        <span class="mt-2 block font-tamil text-3xl font-medium text-stone-700 sm:text-4xl">
          கவுண்டர்
        </span>
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-4 max-w-2xl text-base text-stone-600 sm:text-lg">
        A title, not a caste. In the Kongu region, "Gounder" indexes Kongu Vellala identity — but the same title is used by several other Tamil communities with entirely different histories. This is a clarifying section many community members get wrong.
      </p>
    </header>

    {/* Etymology */}
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">
        Etymology
        <span class="ml-2 font-tamil text-xl font-medium text-stone-600">சொல் வரலாறு</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="prose prose-stone prose-editorial has-dropcap mt-4 max-w-none text-stone-800 sm:text-lg">
        <p>
          The Tamil form is <strong>kavundan / kāvundan</strong> (கவுண்டன்), with the honorific plural <strong>kavundar</strong> (கவுண்டர்). The most-cited internal Tamil derivation glosses it as "village headman" or "land-holder", connecting it to the role of the local Naattaanmai (நாட்டாண்மை) or Pattakaarar (பட்டக்காரர்).
        </p>
        <p>
          A second school of etymology, more frequently noted in academic writing, traces the title to the Kannada/Tulu <strong>Gowda</strong> via the Ganga dynasty's <em>Gangadikara Gowda</em> headmen — a Kannada land-tenure title that diffused into Tamil-speaking Kongu through political contact during the Hoysala and pre-Vijayanagara periods. On this reading, Gounder / Gowda are the same title in different regional pronunciations.
        </p>
        <p>
          The two etymologies are not mutually exclusive — a Kannada-origin word can settle into Tamil and acquire local re-glosses — and neither is securely demonstrable from the surviving record alone. <FactTier tier="yellow" />
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    {/* Function */}
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">
        Function — village headman, chief adjudicator
        <span class="ml-2 font-tamil text-xl font-medium text-stone-600">பங்கு</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="prose prose-stone mt-4 max-w-none text-stone-800 sm:text-lg">
        <p>
          In the Kongu countryside, the Gounder was historically the village-level adjudicator — convening kootam panchayats, settling marriage and land disputes, and acting as the lineage's representative in inter-village affairs. The position was hereditary within particular households but with community ratification: a Naattaanmai or Pattakaarar who lost the confidence of the kootam could be replaced.
        </p>
        <p>
          <Claim tier="yellow" sources={["kootam-totem-system", "kootam-exogamy-rule"]}>
            The Gounder's authority operated within the 145-kootam structure: enforcing exogamy across kootams, recording lineage through Kuladeivam shrine visits, and adjudicating disputes between kootams within the Kongu Vellala community.
          </Claim>
          The role is less prominent in the modern administrative-state era — formal courts and panchayati raj have absorbed most of its dispute-resolution functions — but ritual and marriage authority within the community persists, particularly in rural areas.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    {/* Critical: distinguishing communities */}
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">
        Other communities using the Gounder title
        <span class="ml-2 font-tamil text-xl font-medium text-stone-600">வேறு சமூகங்கள்</span>
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-2 max-w-2xl text-stone-600">
        This is the section that gets confused most often. "Gounder" is a title shared across several unrelated Tamil communities — they share a word, not a lineage. A Kongu Vellala Gounder and a Vettuva Gounder are not in the same caste.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-6 overflow-hidden rounded-2xl border border-stone-200 bg-white">
        <table class="w-full text-sm">
          <thead class="bg-stone-50 text-left text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-stone-500">
            <tr>
              <th class="px-4 py-3">Community</th>
              <th class="hidden px-4 py-3 md:table-cell">Region</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3">Note</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y divide-stone-200">
            {communities.map((c) => (
              <tr class={c.highlight ? 'bg-rose-50' : ''}>
                <td class="px-4 py-3">
                  <p class={`font-medium ${c.highlight ? 'text-rose-900' : 'text-stone-900'}`}>
                    {c.en}
                    {c.highlight && (
                      <span class="ml-2 rounded-full bg-rose-200 px-1.5 py-0.5 text-[10px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-rose-900">
                        your community
                      </span>
                    )}
                  </p>
                  <p class="font-tamil text-xs text-stone-600">{c.ta}</p>
                </td>
                <td class="hidden px-4 py-3 text-stone-700 md:table-cell">{c.region}</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-stone-700">{c.note}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-stone-600">
        Vanniyar communities are sometimes also referenced under "Gounder" in colloquial speech, but the formal Vanniyar Kula Kshatriya identification is distinct from the Gounder title; we leave that to the Vanniyar deep-dive (TBD).
      </p>
    </section>

    {/* Modern transition */}
    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">
        Modern transition — from cultivator to industrialist
        <span class="ml-2 font-tamil text-xl font-medium text-stone-600">தற்காலம்</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="prose prose-stone mt-4 max-w-none text-stone-800 sm:text-lg">
        <p>
          The 20th-century economic history of the Kongu Vellala Gounder community is one of the more remarkable agrarian-to-industrial transitions in modern South India. Capital accumulated in late-19th-century cotton and turmeric trade was reinvested in cotton ginning, then in textile mills, then in pump-set manufacture, then in knitwear export. By the 1990s, <strong>Coimbatore</strong> was a national centre of textile machinery and pump manufacturing, and <strong>Tiruppur</strong> alone accounted for a major share of India's knitwear exports. <FactTier tier="green" />
        </p>
        <p>
          The economic history here is well-documented in industrial-economics literature on Tamil Nadu — Tiruppur's growth has been the subject of dozens of academic papers as a case of agrarian-capital-led mid-tech industrialisation without significant external industrial parentage. The Gounder community was the dominant ownership cohort throughout this transition.
        </p>
        <p>
          The community's contemporary BC/MBC reservation classification, voting patterns, and political organisation (notably around the Kongu Munnetra Kazhagam and other Kongu-specific outfits) are downstream of this economic transition rather than upstream of it. We treat the political-economy dimension in the Reservation page; here we flag only that the Gounder title today carries a substantial industrial-capital connotation that the 19th-century usage did not.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    {/* Cross-links */}
    <section class="rounded-2xl border border-stone-200 bg-white p-6">
      <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-stone-900">Connected pages</h2>
      <ul class="mt-3 grid gap-3 sm:grid-cols-3">
        <li>
          <a href="/lineage/kongu" class="block rounded-xl border border-stone-200 px-4 py-3 hover:border-amber-300 hover:bg-amber-50 focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-indigo-500 focus-visible:ring-offset-2 focus-visible:ring-offset-stone-50">
            <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-stone-500">Region</p>
            <p class="font-medium text-stone-900">Kongu Nadu</p>
            <p class="mt-1 text-xs text-stone-600">Where the Gounder title is most prevalent.</p>
          </a>
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="/lineage/vellala" class="block rounded-xl border border-stone-200 px-4 py-3 hover:border-amber-300 hover:bg-amber-50 focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-indigo-500 focus-visible:ring-offset-2 focus-visible:ring-offset-stone-50">
            <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-stone-500">Caste cluster</p>
            <p class="font-medium text-stone-900">Vellala</p>
            <p class="mt-1 text-xs text-stone-600">The cultivator caste-cluster behind the Kongu Vellala Gounder.</p>
          </a>
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="/lineage/konur" class="block rounded-xl border border-stone-200 px-4 py-3 hover:border-rose-300 hover:bg-rose-50 focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-indigo-500 focus-visible:ring-offset-2 focus-visible:ring-offset-stone-50">
            <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-stone-500">Kuladeivam</p>
            <p class="font-medium text-stone-900">Konur Kaliamman</p>
            <p class="mt-1 text-xs text-stone-600">Kadai Kootam clan deity.</p>
          </a>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <RelatedNav
      readNext={{
        href: '/lineage/kootams',
        title: 'The 145 kootams',
        sub: 'Browse the totemic clans inside the Kongu Vellala Gounder structure.',
      }}
      related={{
        label: 'Related lineage',
        items: [
          { href: '/lineage/konur', title: 'Konur Kaliamman — Kadai Kootam shrine' },
        ],
      }}
      backTo={{ href: '/lineage', label: 'Lineage hub' }}
    />
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
